   в”Њв”Ђ /Users/stuart/parallel_development/flapjack_dev/may25_1248pm_owasp_top10_audit/flapjack_dev/engine/Cargo.lock:45:1
   в”‚
45 в”‚ aws-lc-sys 0.37.1 registry+https://github.com/rust-lang/crates.io-index
   в”‚ в”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓ security vulnerability detected
   в”‚
   в”њ ID: RUSTSEC-2026-0045
   в”њ Advisory: https://rustsec.org/advisories/RUSTSEC-2026-0045
   в”њ Observable timing discrepancy in AES-CCM decryption in AWS-LC allows an
     unauthenticated user to potentially determine authentication tag validity
     via timing analysis.
     
     The impacted implementations are through the EVP CIPHER API:
     `EVP_aes_128_ccm`, `EVP_aes_192_ccm`, and `EVP_aes_256_ccm`.
     
     Customers of AWS services do not need to take action. `aws-lc-sys` contains
     code from AWS-LC. Applications using `aws-lc-sys` should upgrade to the most
     recent release of `aws-lc-sys`.
     
     ## Workarounds
     
     In the special cases of using AES-CCM with (M=4, L=2), (M=8, L=2), or
     (M=16, L=2), applications can workaround this issue by using AES-CCM through
     the EVP AEAD API using implementations `EVP_aead_aes_128_ccm_bluetooth`,
     `EVP_aead_aes_128_ccm_bluetooth_8`, and `EVP_aead_aes_128_ccm_matter`
     respectively.
     
     Otherwise, there is no workaround and applications using `aws-lc-sys` should
     upgrade to the most recent release.
   в”њ Announcement: https://aws.amazon.com/security/security-bulletins/2026-005-AWS
   в”њ Solution: Upgrade to >=0.38.0 (try `cargo update -p aws-lc-sys`)
