error[vulnerability]: CRL Distribution Point Scope Check Logic Error in AWS-LC
   в”Њв”Ђ /Users/stuart/parallel_development/flapjack_dev/may25_1248pm_owasp_top10_audit/flapjack_dev/engine/Cargo.lock:45:1
   в”‚
45 в”‚ aws-lc-sys 0.37.1 registry+https://github.com/rust-lang/crates.io-index
   в”‚ в”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓ security vulnerability detected
   в”‚
   в”њ ID: RUSTSEC-2026-0048
   в”њ Advisory: https://rustsec.org/advisories/RUSTSEC-2026-0048
   в”њ A logic error in CRL distribution point matching in AWS-LC allows a revoked
     certificate to bypass revocation checks during certificate validation, when
     the application enables CRL checking and uses partitioned CRLs with Issuing
     Distribution Point (IDP) extensions.
     
     Customers of AWS services do not need to take action. `aws-lc-sys` contains
     code from AWS-LC. Applications using `aws-lc-sys` should upgrade to the most
     recent release of `aws-lc-sys`.
     
     ## Workarounds
     
     Applications can workaround this issue if they do not enable CRL checking
     (`X509_V_FLAG_CRL_CHECK`). Applications using complete (non-partitioned)
     CRLs without IDP extensions are also not affected.
     
     Otherwise, there is no workaround and applications using `aws-lc-sys` should
     upgrade to the most recent releases of `aws-lc-sys`.
   в”њ Announcement: https://aws.amazon.com/security/security-bulletins/2026-010-AWS
   в”њ Solution: Upgrade to >=0.39.0 (try `cargo update -p aws-lc-sys`)
   в”њ aws-lc-sys v0.37.1
