    в”Њв”Ђ /Users/stuart/parallel_development/flapjack_dev/may25_1248pm_owasp_top10_audit/flapjack_dev/engine/Cargo.lock:500:1
    в”‚
500 в”‚ tar 0.4.44 registry+https://github.com/rust-lang/crates.io-index
    в”‚ в”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓ security vulnerability detected
    в”‚
    в”њ ID: RUSTSEC-2026-0067
    в”њ Advisory: https://rustsec.org/advisories/RUSTSEC-2026-0067
    в”њ In versions 0.4.44 and below of tar-rs, when unpacking a tar archive, the tar
      crate's `unpack_dir` function uses [`fs::metadata()`][fs-metadata] to check
      whether a path that already exists is a directory. Because `fs::metadata()`
      follows symbolic links, a crafted tarball containing a symlink entry followed
      by a directory entry with the same name causes the crate to treat the symlink
      target as a valid existing directory вЂ” and subsequently apply chmod to it. This
      allows an attacker to modify the permissions of arbitrary directories outside
      the extraction root.
      
      This issue has been fixed in version 0.4.45.
      
      [fs-metadata]: https://doc.rust-lang.org/std/fs/fn.metadata.html
    в”њ Solution: Upgrade to >=0.4.45 (try `cargo update -p tar`)
    в”њ tar v0.4.44
